\begin_layout Subsection
Claim on the Firm Assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Debt and equity can be considered as the right to claim the firm's 
\series bold
incomes
\series default
: debt holders have claims to the interest payments (and capital at maturity),
 while equity holders have claims to the 
\series bold
residual
\series default
 income, 
\series bold
after
\series default
 the interest payment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is not enough income to pay the debt, the equity holders get nothing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, debt holders are the first to have claims on the firm's assets,
 and equity holders are the residual claimants.
 In case the firm's value is less than the debt, the debt holders might
 take over the firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Debt holders can never receive more than their debt, regardless of the firm's
 income (their cash flow is 
\series bold
bounded
\series default
).
 Equity holders might receive nothing (depending on the firm's income),
 but as it grows - their cash flow is 
\series bold
unbounded
\series default
.
\end_layout

