\begin_layout Subsection
Equity vs.
 Debt Financing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume a firm is considering the following investment opportunity: invest
 $800 today which will generate either $1400 or $900, depending on the economy
 (both options are equally likely).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the risk-free rate is 5%, and a 10% premium is demanded on top of
 the risk-free rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected cash flow is 1150 (mean), thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $NPV$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
NPV=-800+\frac{1150}{1+15\%}=200
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Unlevered Firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of the project is the present value of its future cash flows,
 which is 1000.
 If the firm is all-equity, how much would it be willing to pay for the
 project? The expected return to the shareholders is the same as the firm's
 return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Levered Firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the investment is financed using debt ($500 with the expected return
 being 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{p}=5\%$
\end_inset

, notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}\neq YTM$
\end_inset

) - the project cash flow will always be enough to pay the debt).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{D}=0$
\end_inset

 and the rest of the finance comes from equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared to the unlevered case, there is more risk to shareholders.
 The expected return on the assets is the same, though the expected return
 on equity is higher.
 There is no risk of default - leverage increases the systematic risk, thus
 the expected return for the equity holders.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is now higher, as the investment is riskier.
 Debt is not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bad
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it only increases both risk and the expected return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modigliani and Miller Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
perfect market
\series default
 assumes: the firm operates forever, generating a constant (not-growing)
 CF.
 It doens't invest in positive (or negative) 
\begin_inset Formula $NPV$
\end_inset

 projects and distributes all its cash flow to debt and equity holders.
 Also, we assume a perfect market with symmetric information, no transaction
 costs, no taxes and no bankrupcy costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

 The required return on the debt of the firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $r_{U}$
\end_inset

 The required return on equity in an unlevered firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $r_{E}$
\end_inset

 The required return on the firm's equity in a levered firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $WACC$
\end_inset

 Weighted average cost of capital of the firm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
WACC=\frac{D}{E+D}r_{D}+\frac{E}{E+D}r_{E}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The periodic payments for all participants are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cash flow: 
\begin_inset Formula $CF$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Debt holders: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}\times D$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Equity holders: 
\begin_inset Formula $CF-r_{D}\times D$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming perpetuity, the firm's market value is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=A=\frac{CF}{r_{U}}=\frac{CF}{WACC}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The debt market value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\frac{r_{D}\times D}{r_{D}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the equity market value:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\frac{CF-r_{D}\times D}{r_{E}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a levered firm, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{L}=E+D$
\end_inset

 and in an unlevered firm: 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{U}=E$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
M&M Proposition I
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a perfect market 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{U}=V_{L}$
\end_inset

 holds (the capital structure is not significant), by the following argument:
 If the total CF generated by the assets equals the total CF paid out to
 all security holders - by the law of one price, securities and assets must
 have the same market value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
No Arbitrage Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider two firms with the exact same projects.
 If A is an all equity firm with a market value of $1000, and firm B has
 $525 debt and $480 equity - there is an arbitrage opportunity from buying
 firm B and short selling A's equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Homemade Leverage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a perfect market, the investor can construct the capital structure she
 wants, no matter what is the capital structure of the firm (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

homemade leverage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice it is done by 
\series bold
replicating
\series default
 the payoff of a leveraged firm, by leveraging her own portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investor won't pay more for (un)leveraged firm, because one can do it
 on herself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
M&M Proposition I - Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r_{A}=r_{U}$
\end_inset

 for every firm in a specific industry, thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{CF}{r_{U}}=V_{U}=V_{L}=\frac{CF}{WACC}\Rightarrow WACC=r_{U}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, for example, if some firm has twice bigger cash flow than the other
 one - its value should be twice as well (simplifying assumption - ignoring
 economies of scale).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $WACC$
\end_inset

 can be calculated in another way, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{A}=\beta_{U}=\frac{D}{E+D}\times\beta_{D}+\frac{E}{E+D}\times\beta_{E}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
M&M Proposition I - Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider two coffee producers: SB and DD.
 SB is all-equity with annual operating profit of $100 and 10% ROA.
 DD, financed with equity and debt, has profit of $300, perpetual debt of
 1000 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}=5\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ROA of DD, assuming returns in the industry are the same is 10%.
 Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{U}(SB)=\frac{CF(SB)}{r_{U}}=1000\Rightarrow V_{U}(DD)=3V_{U}(SB)=3000
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{U}(DD)=300/0.1=3000
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{L}(DD)=V_{U}(DD)=3000
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to calculate the ROE of DD, first find out the equity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=V-D=2000
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
WACC(DD)=r_{U}=10\%
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
WACC(DD)=\frac{2}{3}r_{E}+\frac{0.05}{3}=r_{U}=0.1\Rightarrow r_{E}=0.125
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
M&M Proposition II
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost of capital of levered equity increases with the debt-equity ratio
 of the firm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{E}=r_{U}+\frac{D}{E}(r_{U}-r_{D})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, the levered equity return equals the unlevered return plus
 a premium.
 This is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 as well:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{E}=\beta_{U}+\frac{D}{E}\times(\beta_{U}-\beta_{D})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

